                  </persName>
            . I am a waiter at the public-house; I saw the prisoner come up the passage, and go out at the street door with a blue bundle under his arm - he came back without the bundle; the things have never been found since.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300114-235-person1590">
                  RICHARD 
                  MALLETT
               <interp inst="t18300114-235-person1590" type="surname" value="MALLETT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300114-235-person1590" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300114-235-person1590" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. On the 9th of December the prisoner came and offered six shirts to pawn; one white one, one flannel one, and four dark cotton ones - I did not like his appearance, and offered him half the money he asked, and he went away.</p>
               <p>GEORGE DEVERELL. I am an officer. I took the prisoner; when he was brought by the headborough he said he had been searched - he said the bundle he took out belonged to a girl in the public-house, named Sarah, but he could not tell where she lived, nor her other name; I asked what it contained - he said the image of a broken cow; I went and found the girl and brought her - she said to him,"You need not wink at me. I will not tell a lie for you, my bundle contained a broken cow and nothing else."</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I and my brother William went<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183001140109"></xptr>there to breakfast; a young woman came in and said,"William, if any one comes and asks for me, tell them I am gone up Ratcliff-highway:" when the girl came back she had a bundle with a lot of images in it, and she pulled out five images and a broken cow, to ornament the taproom.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300114-235-verdict1257" type="verdictDescription">
